                "href": "/profile/Jayne-Carmichael-Norrie"
            },
            "answer_text": "Because they use the transversus abdominis (corset muscle) to pace the exhale of their breath. This is where a lot of singers go wrong. The diaphragm is important for your INHALE but the corset muscle controls your EXHALE. Here\u2019s a way you to try and feel it working. Take a breath in and then let out a hiss sound (sounds like air hissing out of a balloon). Keep going with that sound for as long as you can. While you are hissing out, you might notice your waist and the middle of your body coming in. If you have ever worn a corset, it feels a bit like someone is pulling the strings and the corset is gently tightening around your body. That is the corset muscle. Next, try and sing a note to an \u2018ee\u2019 vowel. Choose a note that\u2019s very comfortable for you. Then start singing the note while gently bringing in the corset muscle to help pace your breathing. Try this a few times and see if it can improve how long you can sing for in one breath. ",
