                "name": "Michael Gordon",
                "href": "/profile/Michael-Gordon-39"
            },
            "answer_text": "I come from the perspective of western classical singing where I was taught the goals of \u201cefficient phonation\u201d and \u201cresonance.\u201d Said in not so fancy language, the goal most of the time is to sing in such a way that not much breath is expelled. Many singers may think that singing needs a lot of air, and they may try to make a big sound by pushing a lot of air out while they sing. In singing, the vocal folds are opening and closing, and in a breathy vocal production the vocal folds may never fully come together so the singer is always leaking air. With \u201cefficient phonation\u201d the vocal folds will come together completely and so much less air is expelled. Resonance is an important part of singing, and this means finding ways to have your body naturally amplify the sound from the vocal folds. To accomplish the goal of efficient phonation, many singing teachers will stress good body alignment and the conscious use of various muscles related to breathing/inhalation. ",
